Lessons Learned and Future Work 9

Challenges and Solutions:

1. The initial approach of using time-series models did not provide the desired predictive accuracy. Switching to classification models significantly enhanced performance and better aligned with the projectâ€™s objectives for inventory optimization.

2. While converting the Python code to the Microsoft Fabric environment, challenges arose in generating the predicted column. The solution involved modifying the code and installing additional libraries to successfully transform the data frame. This allowed for further data processing, including cleaning the dataset, handling missing values in Data Wrangler, and preparing the data for accurate reporting.

3. Some DAX formulas required adjustments to yield precise results. I created additional columns, such as inventory levels, and removed order quantities with a value of zero to accurately calculate the stockout rate KPI. This enhancement allows for easier monitoring of potential stockouts, enabling actionable insights to be taken for inventory management.



Lessons Learned:

  • Compatibility Considerations: When integrating different tools and platforms, such as Python code in Microsoft Fabric, itâ€™s important to anticipate and address compatibility issues early to avoid implementation delays.
  • Flexibility in Code and Formulas: Code and formulas often need adjustments to meet specific project requirements. Being prepared to refine and tweak them as needed is crucial for achieving accurate results.
  • Cross-Functional Collaboration: Effective communication and collaboration among team members across different departments (e.g., data science, engineering, and analysis) are vital for overcoming technical challenges and ensuring project success.
  • Scalability and Adaptability: Solutions should be designed with scalability in mind, allowing for adjustments and expansions as project requirements evolve or as more data becomes available.



Future Capabilities:

The future of this project holds numerous possibilities for expanding efficiency and precision in inventory management. Integrating AI-driven predictive analytics could further refine demand forecasting, helping to avoid stockouts and minimize overstock situations. The use of real-time tracking systems powered by IoT (internet of things) devices could provide more granular insights into warehouse operations, improving responsiveness to supply chain fluctuations. Additionally, advancements in warehouse automation, such as robotics and AI-guided systems, could streamline inventory handling and reduce human errors, resulting in faster fulfillment times and enhanced operational efficiency. Scalability is another potential area for growth, allowing the system to adapt to increasing data volumes and expanding warehouse networks. Enhanced data visualization tools could offer deeper insights, enabling stakeholders to drill down into specific operational bottlenecks and forecast trends more effectively. Lastly, implementing blockchain for inventory traceability could ensure better transparency and security, allowing for smoother supply chain operations across different regions.
